name: Series Zero: Young Lion Of The West
description:
The construction of the Erie Canal brought about prosperity and industry to a small settlement on the banks of the Gennesee River known then as 'Rochesterville.' After the completion of the canal, Rochester (as the name was changed to what we know now) became an industrial boomtown with populations exploding and wealthy businessmen and developers traveling by boat horse or mule coming to stack their claim on this prosperity. Rochester's original and all-encompassing nickname was born: The Young Lion Of The West.

Shirt Color: Heather Black

name: Series Zero: The Flower City
description:
Lilacs are to Rochester as apples are to New York City. An iconic symbol of our botanical expanse, the City of Rochester even adopted the flowering bush as its symbol to represent official city business. Botanical titans like George Ellwanger, Patrick Barry, Frank Olmsted (Landscape Architect of HIghland Park), and Charles Crosman all grew their empires along the banks of the Genesee and contributed to Rochester's third nickname: The Flower City.

Shirt Color: Heather Plum

name: Series Zero: The Flour City
description:
The gear cog is actually a 1820s style waterwheel modeled after the giant sub level Triphammer Forge waterwheel, unearthed after fire razed the Triphammer Building to the ground at Browns Race in the city. Browns Race was the epicenter of Rochester's leavened rise to granular power, harnessing the hydraulic force of High Falls to feed the enormous waterwheels powering grist wheels processing grains into flour.

Shirt Color: Brown

Hundreds of homes catalogued with the National Registry of Historic Places, Aged Sycamore trees lining almost every street, Former home of Brown Brothers Nursery during the Flower City boom, and the vast Ellison Park are just some of the parts that make up the historic Browncroft neighborhood.  Street cars serviced the neighborhood up and down Winton and Blossom until after World War II when the streets were reclaimed for buses and cars.  

The Browncroft/Rowlands shirt is a traditional brown for both mens and womens to commemorate its historic houses and sycamore trees known in the area.  The green accent commemorates the existence of the Brown Brothers Nursery and Ellison Park.
